article.description:
Tamika Catchings scored 25 points,
including the go-ahead basket in the second overtime, as the
Indiana Fever held off the Connecticut Sun 94-90 on Thursday night.
article.headline: Catchings has 25 points and 16 boards in win
article.linkText: Catchings powers Fever past Sun in double OT
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- A bandage covering a gash beneath
Tamika Catchings' left eye would not stay on as sweat streamed down
her face.

A sore left hamstring made her limp down the court but not off
it. Indiana's wounded star simply refused to lose.

She scored 25 points, including the go-ahead basket in the
second overtime, as the Fever held off the Connecticut Sun 94-90 on
Thursday night.

Catchings also paced the Fever (6-5) with a career-high 16
rebounds and scored seven of Indiana's 14 points in the second
overtime. Her driving layup with 33.9 seconds left broke an 88-88
tie. Four free throws from Stephanie White and Kristen Rasmussen
iced the game in the closing seconds.

"She is just a warrior," Fever coach Nell Fortner said. "She
pursues the ball so well. Her pursuit is what makes her standout.
She has the ability to take it to another level."

One of the most popular players in the league, Catchings leads
all Eastern Conference players with more than 48,000 votes in
All-Star game balloting.

The former Tennessee All-American also is a big hit with her
teammates.

"She really doesn't surprise me anymore," said Coretta Brown,
who scored a career-high 25 points for Indiana. "She gives us
whatever we need."

Katie Douglas led Connecticut (6-6) with 25 points, a
career-high that included 6-of-9 3-pointers. Her 3-pointer with 1
second remaining in regulation tied it at 73 and sent the game into
overtime. It was Douglas' second start since coming off the injured
list with a chipped bone in her left foot.

Catchings was scoreless in the first OT, but started the Fever
off with a 3-point play in the second. After a 3-pointer by
Rasmussen, Catchings rebounded her own miss and give Indiana an
88-86 lead with 1:14 left. She then fouled Douglas, who hit a
jumper but missed the free throw.

Catchings then drove the lane for the winning basket, falling
into a pile of players. She came up limping, holding her left
hamstring but played out the final minutes.

"What's best about this team is that we stuck together,"
Catchings said. "We could have put our heads down at the end of
regulation, but we came out and pulled it out as a team."

Sun forward Taj McWilliams-Franklin finished with 20 points and
eight rebounds. After winning Tuesday's game against Washington
with a basket with 2.4 seconds left, McWilliams-Franklin came up
big again in the late going, hitting a layup with 0.4 seconds
remaining in the first OT to send the game into another extra
session.

Brown had 18 points and four of the Fever's six 3-pointers in
the first half as Indiana built a 39-27 lead at the break. Brown's
3-pointer with 11:04 left in the half kicked off a 19-2 run.

It was the second straight overtime loss at home for
Connecticut.

"Catchings can make you change your lineup," Sun coach Mike
Thibault said. "I have to find a group that can matchup, rebound
the ball and be successful."

Shannon Johnson scored 24 points for the Sun. Her free throws
with 1:57 left in the first overtime put Connecticut up 77-75, its
first lead since midway through the first half.

"We had our chances," Johnson said. "We just couldn't
capitalize when we needed to."
